<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="58" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,452]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,220,244]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">Distribution.</emphasis>
New for 
<collectingCountry box="[458,531,221,244]" name="Ghana" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">Ghana</collectingCountry>
. The species, although not rare, was known until now only from the central and eastern part of equatorial Africa. The new data significantly enlarges its range towards the west. It suggests that the species inhabits a much wider area, possibly sympatric with 
<taxonomicName box="[796,930,290,313]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Anace" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis box="[796,930,290,313]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,452]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,324,348]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
Uncus which is devoid of long lobes separates 
<emphasis box="[820,983,325,348]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">P. ka m i t u g e n s i s</emphasis>
from the remaining representatives of the genus. The specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[454,524,360,383]" name="Ghana" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">Ghana</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[539,603,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,1660,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,1615,1925]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. (A) Pseudothyretes kamitugensis. (B) Rhipidarctia (Hemirhipidia) postrosea. (C) Metarctia paremphares. (D) Metarctia priscilla. (E) Metarctia sp. (scale bar = 10 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206671/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[590,603,360,383]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A) slightly differ from the East African ones in general colouration. They are darker and lack the paler tinge on the upper part of the forewing. The taxonomic status of the West African population will be resolved during a revisionary study of 
<taxonomicName box="[642,804,429,452]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudothyretes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[642,804,429,452]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="58">Pseudothyretes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is currently under preparation.
</paragraph>
